I treated `AR-034` through `AR-043` as the deployment/E2E slice anchored by `specs/deployment/spec.md`, plus the repo’s documented `run_e2e.sh` setup details from `specs/ci-cd/design.md`. On that basis, I filled in the missing E2E package and tightened the verification layer rather than only relying on the existing shallow asset checks.

I updated `deployment_assets_test.go` to assert the required `test/e2e` assets and the richer setup flow in `test/e2e/run_e2e.sh`. I then expanded `test/e2e/run_e2e.sh` so it now provisions a Kind cluster, installs `agent-sandbox`, builds and loads the local images, deploys Redis, installs the Helm chart, applies runtime fixtures, creates the test service account/token, port-forwards the services, and runs Go/Python smoke tests. I also added the missing E2E package contents: `test/e2e/README.md`, `test/e2e/__init__.py`, `test/e2e/e2e_test.go`, `test/e2e/test_codeinterpreter.py`, `test/e2e/echo_agent.yaml`, `test/e2e/e2e_code_interpreter.yaml`, and `test/e2e/e2e_code_interpreter_warmpool.yaml`.

I could not live-run `go test ./...` or `make e2e` here because non-allowlisted shell commands were blocked in this environment, so the verification is static: spec-to-code alignment, test hardening, and a self-review pass over the changed files. If you want, I can do a follow-up pass once command execution is available and validate the full Go suite plus the E2E script end to end.
